### 1. Server binds to all interfaces implicitly (Low/Medium)
`app.listen(3000, ...)` binds to `0.0.0.0` by default, exposing the service on every network interface. If this is only meant to serve localhost, bind explicitly:

```js
app.listen(3000, '127.0.0.1', () => {
  console.log('Server running on http://127.0.0.1:3000');
});
```

### 2. No security response headers (Medium — OWASP A05: Security Misconfiguration)
Express ships with no hardening headers. Add `helmet`:

```js
const helmet = require('helmet');
app.use(helmet());
```

This sets `X-Content-Type-Options`, `Strict-Transport-Security`, `X-Frame-Options`, a default CSP, etc.

### 3. No CORS policy configured (Low/Medium)
`/users` currently responds to any origin since no CORS middleware is set — the default is same-origin, but there's no explicit allow/deny. Be explicit:

```js
const cors = require('cors');
app.use(cors({ origin: ['https://your.app'], methods: ['GET'] }));
```

### 4. PII returned without authentication (High — OWASP A01: Broken Access Control / A02: Cryptographic Failures via plaintext transport)
`/users` returns email addresses to any unauthenticated caller. Even with hardcoded data, this is the wrong default pattern. Gate it:

```js
function requireAuth(req, res, next) {
  const token = req.headers.authorization?.replace(/^Bearer\s+/i, '');
  if (!token || !verifyJwt(token)) return res.status(401).json({ error: 'unauthorized' });
  req.user = decodeJwt(token);
  next();
}

app.get('/users', requireAuth, (req, res) => { /* ... */ });
```

Also serve behind TLS in production; don't rely on `app.listen` directly in prod — terminate TLS at a reverse proxy or use `https.createServer`.

### 5. No rate limiting (Medium — OWASP A04: Insecure Design)
Both endpoints are unbounded. Add `express-rate-limit`:

```js
const rateLimit = require('express-rate-limit');
app.use(rateLimit({ windowMs: 60_000, max: 60 }));
```

### 6. No request logging / monitoring (Low — OWASP A09)
No visibility into who is calling what. Add structured logging:

```js
const pino = require('pino-http')();
app.use(pino);
```

### 7. `console.log` server banner leaks info (Informational)
`Server running on port 3000` is fine in dev. In production, route through a logger with levels and avoid advertising internal ports in any response/error.

### 8. Error handling is absent (Medium — OWASP A05/A09)
There is no error middleware. Unhandled errors in a real handler would bubble up and Express's default handler leaks stack traces in development. Add:

```js
app.use((err, req, res, _next) => {
  req.log?.error({ err }, 'request failed');
  res.status(500).json({ error: 'internal_error' });
