# Security Review: `app.js`

Honest assessment first: this is a 23-line Express app with two static GET endpoints, no user input handling, no database, no authentication, no templating, and no file system access. **Most OWASP Top 10 categories (injection, SSRF, deserialization, XXE) don't apply because the attack surface doesn't exist yet.** I'll flag only what's actually relevant rather than inventing vulnerabilities.

---

## Real findings

### 1. `/users` exposes PII with no authentication (OWASP A01: Broken Access Control + A02: Cryptographic Failures / data exposure)
The endpoint returns email addresses to any unauthenticated caller. Even with seed data, this is the pattern that will ship to production.

```js
// Current
app.get('/users', (req, res) => { res.json([...emails...]); });

// Recommended — require auth and scope the response
const requireAuth = require('./middleware/requireAuth');
app.get('/users', requireAuth, (req, res) => {
  const publicView = users.map(({ id, name }) => ({ id, name })); // drop email
  res.json(publicView);
});
```

### 2. No security headers (OWASP A05: Security Misconfiguration)
Express sends no security headers by default and leaks `X-Powered-By: Express`.

```js
const helmet = require('helmet');
app.disable('x-powered-by');
app.use(helmet()); // CSP, HSTS, X-Frame-Options, X-Content-Type-Options, etc.
```

### 3. No rate limiting (OWASP A04: Insecure Design)
`/users` and `/health` can be hammered indefinitely — useful for scraping PII or DoS.

```js
const rateLimit = require('express-rate-limit');
app.use(rateLimit({ windowMs: 60_000, max: 60, standardHeaders: true }));
```

### 4. No CORS policy declared (A05)
Currently no `Access-Control-Allow-Origin` header is set, so browser cross-origin reads are blocked — but as soon as someone adds `cors()` casually they'll likely use `*`. Be explicit:

```js
const cors = require('cors');
app.use(cors({ origin: ['https://your-frontend.example.com'], credentials: false }));
```

### 5. `app.listen(3000)` binds to all interfaces, hardcoded port (A05)
Binds `0.0.0.0` by default — fine behind a reverse proxy, risky on a dev box on public Wi‑Fi. Also, port should come from env.

```js
const port = process.env.PORT || 3000;
const host = process.env.HOST || '127.0.0.1';
app.listen(port, host, () => console.log(`listening on ${host}:${port}`));
```

### 6. No error-handling middleware (A05 / A09 Logging & Monitoring)
An uncaught error in a future route will bubble to Express's default handler, which includes stack traces in development. Add a final handler:

```js
app.use((err, req, res, _next) => {
  req.log?.error({ err }, 'unhandled');
  res.status(500).json({ error: 'internal_error' }); // no stack to client
});
```

### 7. `console.log` instead of structured logging (A09)
