# Security Review: `app.js`

I've reviewed the entire file (23 lines). Here's a thorough, honest assessment.

## Summary

This is a minimal Express app with two endpoints (`/health`, `/users`) that return static data. There are **no database queries, no user input parsing, no authentication flow, no file I/O, and no templating** — which means most of the classic OWASP Top 10 attack surface simply isn't present yet. That said, there are still a handful of legitimate hardening issues worth addressing, and more importantly, several concerns that will matter the moment this app grows.

## Findings in the current code

### 1. Missing security headers (OWASP A05: Security Misconfiguration) — Low/Medium
No `helmet` middleware, so responses lack `X-Content-Type-Options`, `Strict-Transport-Security`, `X-Frame-Options`, CSP, etc.

**Fix:**
```js
const helmet = require('helmet');
app.use(helmet());
```

### 2. No CORS policy defined (A05) — Informational
If this will be called by browsers from another origin, CORS needs an explicit allowlist. If it's server-to-server only, ignore this.

**Fix (explicit allowlist):**
```js
const cors = require('cors');
app.use(cors({ origin: ['https://your-frontend.example.com'], methods: ['GET'] }));
```

### 3. PII exposure on `/users` (A01: Broken Access Control, A02: Cryptographic Failures) — Medium
`/users` returns real-looking email addresses with **no authentication, no authorization, and no rate limiting**. Even if the data is seed data today, this endpoint shape encourages the same pattern to be copy-pasted when real user data is added.

**Fix — require auth and scope the response:**
```js
function requireAuth(req, res, next) {
  const token = req.headers.authorization?.replace(/^Bearer\s+/i, '');
  if (!token || !isValidToken(token)) return res.sendStatus(401);
  req.user = decodeToken(token);
  next();
}

app.get('/users', requireAuth, (req, res) => {
  // Only return fields the caller is authorized to see
  res.json(users.map(u => ({ id: u.id, name: u.name })));
});
```

### 4. No rate limiting / DoS protection (A04: Insecure Design) — Low
Any client can hammer `/health` or `/users`.

**Fix:**
```js
const rateLimit = require('express-rate-limit');
app.use(rateLimit({ windowMs: 60_000, max: 100 }));
```

### 5. Hard-coded port, no env configuration (A05) — Low
`app.listen(3000, ...)` — should come from `process.env.PORT` so deployments can bind appropriately and so you can bind to `127.0.0.1` in local/dev contexts.

**Fix:**
```js
const PORT = Number(process.env.PORT) || 3000;
const HOST = process.env.HOST || '0.0.0.0';
app.listen(PORT, HOST, () => console.log(`Server running on ${HOST}:${PORT}`));
```

### 6. `x-powered-by: Express` header leaks framework (A05) — Informational
Fingerprinting aid for attackers. `helmet()` removes it; otherwise:
```js
app.disable('x-powered-by');
```

### 7. No error handler / no graceful shutdown (A09: Logging & Monitoring Failures) — Low
Unhandled errors will default-leak stack traces in some Express configs, and there's no `process.on('SIGTERM', ...)` to drain connections.

**Fix:**
```js
